ational name from Hastings (Sussex), near which the English army was defeated by the Normans in 1066. The placename derives from an Old English personal name <i>Hǣsta</i> + the Old English groupname suffix <i>-ingas</i>. In the latter part of the 12th century, at the time of William the Lion, the surname was taken to Scotland, where it assimilated instances of the native Scottish surname <b>Harestane</b>.","English: variant of   Hasting   with Middle English genitival <i>-s</i>.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hOistín</b> ‘descendant of <i>Oistín</i>’, the Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Augustine</i> (see   Austin  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Hasting","meanings":["English: from the Norman personal name <i>Hastang</i>, <i>Hastenc</i>, <i>Hasten</i> (Old Norse <i>Hásteinn</i> ‘high’ + ‘stone’). See also   Hastings  ."]},{"name":"Heston","meanings":["English: habitational name from Heston (Middlesex) or Histon (Cambridgeshire). The Middlesex placename derives from Old English <i>hǣs</i> ‘brushwood’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, while the Cambridgeshire placename may derive from Old English <i>hyse</i> ‘shoot, tendril’, also ‘son, youth’, + <i>tūn</i>.","Irish (Mayo): variant of   Hastings  ."]}]},{"name":"Isabelle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabel","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":37,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabelle Hastings was born about 1300, in Suffolk, England, her father, Edmund Hastings, was 37 and her mother, Isabelle Russell, was 34. She married William WAKEMAN in 1320, in Worcestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1347, in her hometown, at the age of 48."},"et":{"about 1300–1347":"umbes 1300–1347","1300–1347":"1300–1347","1295–Male":"1295–Surnud","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1325–1376":"1325–1376","1264–1314":"1264–1314","1267–1305":"1267–1305","24 June 1314":"24. juuni 1314","3 October 1305":"3. oktoober 1305","18 November 1292":"18. november 1292","1264":"1264","1295":"1295","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1325":"1325","1347":"1347","1314":"1314","1267":"1267","1300":"1300","1453":"1453","1376":"1376","1320":"1320","about 1300":"umbes 1300","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Bannockburn, Sterlingshire, Scotland":"Bannockburn, Stirlingshire, Šotimaa, 